---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .rail-box { border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: 18px 20px; background: var(--card); }
    .rail-title { font-weight: 600; font-size: 15px; margin-bottom: 4px; }
    .rail-meta { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: 11px; color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 10px; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; }
    .rail-body { font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.55; }
    .callout-box { background: var(--muted); border-left: 3px solid var(--primary); padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 0 var(--radius-md) var(--radius-md) 0; font-size: 13.5px; color: var(--text-secondary); margin: 12px 0; }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="22 · Dual-Rail Architecture — Sardis Canvas" currentId="dual-rail">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 22 · Protocol</span>
        <h1>Dual-Rail Architecture — internal ledger first.</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          Sardis v1.1 inverts the usual fintech stack: the <strong>internal ledger is the primary rail</strong>,
          and external rails (ACH, card, stablecoin, wire, FX bridge) become on-ramp and off-ramp only. When both
          parties are on Sardis, a payment completes in ~1ms with $0 fee and zero external API calls. When the
          merchant is off-Sardis, we fall back to the cheapest external rail that matches the mandate's
          <code>rail_scope</code>. This is the PayPal model applied to agent commerce.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          Rails are a settlement surface, not a settlement strategy. Most agent payments in a mature ecosystem
          will be Sardis-to-Sardis — the same way most PayPal dollars never leave PayPal. External rails stay
          as ramps; internal ledger carries the volume.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Two rails -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">The two rails</div>
          <h2>Primary vs. fallback.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="rail-box">
            <div class="rail-meta">Primary rail</div>
            <div class="rail-title">Sardis internal ledger</div>
            <div class="rail-body">
              An atomic, double-entry ledger inside Sardis. Payer's FundingCells (UTXO) debit in one row;
              merchant's Sardis balance credits in another. Both writes happen in a single PostgreSQL
              transaction with <code>FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED</code> on the cell row.
              <ul style="padding-left:18px; margin:10px 0 0 0;">
                <li><strong>~1ms</strong> end-to-end (database commit latency)</li>
                <li><strong>$0</strong> marginal fee (no external API calls)</li>
                <li><strong>Full audit</strong> — every ledger row hash-chained, Merkle-batched, on-chain anchored</li>
                <li><strong>No chain reorg risk</strong> — database is final</li>
                <li>Reversible via arbitration up to <code>dispute_window</code> expiry</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="rail-box">
            <div class="rail-meta">Fallback rails</div>
            <div class="rail-title">External settlement (when merchant is off-Sardis)</div>
            <div class="rail-body">
              The liquidity router selects the best rail based on: merchant's preferred settlement currency,
              mandate's <code>rail_scope</code>, FX slippage budget, real-time rail health.
              <ul style="padding-left:18px; margin:10px 0 0 0;">
                <li><strong>x402</strong> — stablecoin, HTTP-native</li>
                <li><strong>Card (Stripe Connect, Adyen)</strong> — existing merchant account</li>
                <li><strong>Bank (ACH / RTP / SEPA / PIX / Wire)</strong> — direct deposit</li>
                <li><strong>FX bridge (Bridge.xyz, Wise)</strong> — cross-currency</li>
                <li><strong>MPP (Stripe Merchant Payment Protocol)</strong> — Tempo settlement</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- On-ramps -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">On-ramp</div>
          <h2>How money enters Sardis.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Principals fund their vaults via any rail that makes sense for their treasury. Once on Sardis,
            those funds become FundingCells and circulate between agents and merchants entirely inside the ledger.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-3">
          <div class="card"><div class="card-title">Bank transfer</div><div class="card-description">ACH pull, wire, SEPA, Faster Payments. Settles to principal's custodial vault in 1–3 business days (varies by rail).</div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="card-title">Card funding</div><div class="card-description">Debit card load for quick top-up. Standard card processing fees apply. Covers agents that need liquidity inside minutes.</div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="card-title">USDC / stablecoin</div><div class="card-description">On-chain deposit to a Sardis-controlled smart wallet. Near-instant, low fee. Most common for crypto-native principals.</div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="card-title">Credit line</div><div class="card-description">A credit-backed mandate draws against a pre-approved revolving line; repayment schedules as a subscription mandate back to the principal's treasury.</div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="card-title">Stablecoin bridges</div><div class="card-description">USDC.e and other variants bridge in via Circle CCTP or LayerZero; normalized to canonical USDC inside Sardis.</div></div>
          <div class="card"><div class="card-title">Smart wallet</div><div class="card-description">An ERC-4337 smart account pre-authorizes Sardis as a spender; agent payments draw down from there without per-tx signatures.</div></div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Off-ramps -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Off-ramp</div>
          <h2>How money leaves Sardis.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:720px;">
            Only when the merchant is off-Sardis. The liquidity router picks the cheapest rail that matches the
            merchant's preferred payout currency and the mandate's <code>rail_scope</code>.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead><tr><th>Rail</th><th>Typical use</th><th>Latency</th><th>Fee pattern</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>x402 (stablecoin)</td><td>API monetization, agent-to-agent micro-pay</td><td>seconds</td><td>~$0.005 per call</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Stripe Connect (card)</td><td>Pay with Sardis merchants, legacy e-commerce</td><td>~3 seconds auth, T+2 payout</td><td>2.9% + $0.30</td></tr>
            <tr><td>ACH (US)</td><td>Large US merchant payouts, vendor settlement</td><td>1–3 business days (Same-day ACH 4 hrs)</td><td>$0.25–$1</td></tr>
            <tr><td>SEPA (EU) / Faster Payments (UK)</td><td>EU/UK merchant payouts</td><td>seconds–hours</td><td>€0.10–€0.50</td></tr>
            <tr><td>RTP (US real-time)</td><td>Critical payouts, gig economy settlement</td><td>seconds</td><td>~$0.50</td></tr>
            <tr><td>PIX (Brazil), UPI (India)</td><td>LATAM / APAC merchant reach</td><td>seconds</td><td>free–$0.10</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Wire (domestic + SWIFT)</td><td>Large B2B, enterprise reconciliation</td><td>hours–1 day</td><td>$15–$40</td></tr>
            <tr><td>FX bridge (Bridge.xyz)</td><td>Cross-currency settlement</td><td>seconds</td><td>~25 bps</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Why -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Why this architecture</div>
          <h2>The PayPal parallel.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="callout-box">
          PayPal processes roughly <strong>95% of its dollar-flow inside its own ledger.</strong> Users top up
          once, receive payments from other PayPal users, then off-ramp occasionally. The external rails (bank,
          card) are funnels, not settlement. PayPal's moat isn't the rails — it's the closed loop.
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Why it matters for agent commerce</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Agents transact at sub-cent granularity. Running every micro-payment through card rails (2.9%+$0.30)
              or ACH (min $0.25) is economically dead. The only way agent commerce scales is if ~90% of volume
              stays on an internal ledger where marginal cost is a database write. Sardis is built around that
              reality from day one.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Why external rails still matter</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Merchants have suppliers, payroll, landlords — obligations that live in fiat. The off-ramp has to
              work every day on time. Sardis doesn't pretend the dollar doesn't exist; it just doesn't route
              agent-to-agent dollars through the ACH network.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Diagram -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">The loop</div>
          <h2>Full diagram.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
flowchart TB
    subgraph Onramp["On-ramp · external → Sardis"]
        BT[Bank transfer]
        CD[Card]
        UC[USDC]
        SC[Stablecoin]
        CR[Credit line]
    end
    subgraph Internal["Sardis internal ledger · primary rail"]
        PV["Payer vault<br/>FundingCells (UTXO)"]
        MB["Merchant account<br/>Sardis balance"]
        PC["Protocol core<br/>+ escrow"]
        ZK["ZKP +<br/>recurring"]
        ID["Identity +<br/>trust"]
        PV -->|"atomic ledger transfer<br/>~1ms, $0 fee"| MB
    end
    subgraph Decision
        D{Merchant<br/>off-Sardis?}
    end
    subgraph Offramp["Off-ramp · Sardis → external (fallback only)"]
        X402[x402]
        CS[Card · Stripe]
        BA["Bank · ACH/RTP"]
        FX[FX bridge]
        WR[Wire]
    end

    BT --> PV
    CD --> PV
    UC --> PV
    SC --> PV
    CR --> PV
    MB --> D
    D -->|No| MB
    D -->|Yes fallback| X402
    D -->|Yes fallback| CS
    D -->|Yes fallback| BA
    D -->|Yes fallback| FX
    D -->|Yes fallback| WR
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Cross-refs</div>
          <h2>Related canvases.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/settlement">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">10 · Flows</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Settlement & Chains</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">Multi-chain executor, CCTP, paymaster, fiat rails — the external side.</div>
          </a>
          <a class="canvas-card" href="/protocol-objects">
            <div class="canvas-card-num">20 · Protocol</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-title">Protocol Objects</div>
            <div class="canvas-card-desc">FundingCell, Settlement Receipt, FXQuote — what flows through these rails.</div>
          </a>
        </div>
      </section>
</Canvas>